  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">William Lloyd Garrison compares the unity of all good people opposed to slavery with that of the early Christians. Garrison agrees with Thomas Shipley&apos;s favorable opinion of Gerrit Smith&apos;s speech before the convention at Peterboro. He agrees, also, on the need for an amendment to the Constitution. Garrison writes: &quot;I like your suggestion, respecting the propriety of holding quarterly meetings of the Managers of the Parent Society, and will allude to it in the Liberator.&quot; Garrison welcomes the reappearance of Benjamin Lundy&apos;s Genius of Universal Emancipation. Garrison comments on Dr. William E. Channing&apos;s &quot;sort of Ishmaelitish work on slavery.&quot;</subfield>
  </datafield>
